section 10_3

  |Global Mean Surface Temperature ({Topics.*Surface_Temperature GMST}) warmed strongly over the period 1900â€“1940, followed by a period with little {Glossary.*Trend trend}, and strong warming since the mid-1970s. Since 1998 the trend in GMST has been small. {Glossary.*Detection_and_Attribution Detection} and {Topics.*Attribution_of_Change attribution studies} show robust detections of the effects of {Glossary.*Greenhouse_gas GHGs} and other {Topics.*Radiative_Forcing anthropogenic forcings} on the distinctive {Glossary.*Fingerprint fingerprint} of atmospheric temperature trends. It is extremely likely that {Topics.*Human_Influence human activities} caused more than half of the observed increase in GMST from 1951 to 2010. {Glossary.*Anthropogenic Anthropogenic} influence on climate has now been detected on all seven continents.


